# User Data Authorization

Any database read or write that involves **user-owned data** must verify the caller with the Clerk session and/or the app `users.role_id` so one user cannot access another user’s records.

## Roles

| Role | Access to other users’ data |
|------|-----------------------------|
| `Public` | Not a DB role — signed-out / anonymous visitors only |
| `default` | Own data only (`clerk_user_id` must match session) |
| `admin` | Staff admin surfaces only; **cannot** edit or assign `super_admin` |
| `super_admin` | Staff admin surfaces; may manage all roles including other staff; exclusive surfaces (e.g. `/dashboard/questions`) |

Use helpers in `src/lib/users.js` (`getCurrentAppUser`, `assertCanAccessUserData`, `canManageUser`, `canAssignRole`, `requireStaffAppUser`, `requireSuperAdminAppUser`) and visibility helpers in `src/lib/roles.js` (`canAccessByRole`, `getViewerVisibilityRole`).

Gate staff-only routes with `requireStaffAppUser()`. Gate `super_admin`-only routes with `requireSuperAdminAppUser()` — do not rely on UI hiding alone.

## Cascading visibility (CMS / nav)

For Prismic Header Menu and similar role-gated UI, access is **cascading** (higher roles see everything below them):

| Viewer | Can see items requiring |
|--------|-------------------------|
| `Public` (signed out) | `Public` |
| `default` | `Public`, `default` |
| `admin` | `Public`, `default`, `admin` |
| `super_admin` | `Public`, `default`, `admin`, `super_admin` |

`Public` is a CMS visibility tier only — it is **not** stored in `user_roles`. Signed-out visitors map to `Public`; signed-in users use their app `roleName`.

```js
import { canAccessByRole, getViewerVisibilityRole } from "@/lib/roles";

const viewerRole = getViewerVisibilityRole(appUser?.roleName); // Public when null
if (!canAccessByRole(viewerRole, item.requiredRole)) return null;
```

## Required pattern

1. Resolve the session with Clerk `auth()` / `currentUser()` — never trust a client-supplied user id alone.
2. Load the app user + role when authorization depends on role.
3. Scope queries with `eq(table.clerkUserId, sessionUserId)` unless the actor is `admin` or `super_admin` **and** the code path is an admin surface.
4. Prefer returning empty / `null` / a safe error over leaking rows.

```js
// ✅ Own data only
const { userId } = await auth();
if (!userId) return [];
return db.select().from(rows).where(eq(rows.clerkUserId, userId));

// ✅ Admin list — only inside an admin page/action after role check
const appUser = await getCurrentAppUser();
if (!isStaffRole(appUser?.roleName)) return [];
return db.select().from(rows); // cross-user OK on this admin path only

// ❌ Never
return db.select().from(rows); // unscoped user data
return db.select().from(rows).where(eq(rows.clerkUserId, formData.get("userId")));
```

## Admin exception

Cross-user queries are allowed **only** when:

- The caller’s role is `admin` or `super_admin`, **and**
- The Server Action / Server Component is part of an admin or staff page (document that in the action)

Do not grant cross-user access from shared helpers used by regular user pages.

## Avoid

- Filtering solely on row `id` without also checking ownership or staff role
- Passing another user’s Clerk id from the client to bypass scope
- Putting admin-wide queries in default-user dashboards
- Skipping auth because a route is “already protected” by middleware — still scope the query
- Letting `admin` edit or assign `super_admin` — use `canManageUser` / `canAssignRole`
- Treating `Public` as a database role or inserting it into `user_roles`
